had been doing in a lot of companies, which 
was building stuff for three years and then  

184
00:14:56,400 --> 00:15:00,920
releasing it in a big bang. What all of 
the people who signed the Agile Manifesto  

185
00:15:00,920 --> 00:15:06,280
realized was if we do it the other way, if we do 
a waterfall type environment, agile waterfall,  

186
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:10,360
that's where we go across, there's a lot of risk 
because we don't test it with the customer and we  

187
00:15:10,360 --> 00:15:15,000
don't get feedback on it if we spend three years 
building it and never show it to somebody. It  

188
00:15:15,000 --> 00:15:20,560
really approached a different way of building 
software. It said let's chunk it down and try  

189
00:15:20,560 --> 00:15:27,040
to get feedback faster. Really noble intention.
In the Scrum guide though, it introduces these  

190
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:32,440
new roles. We have developers as we know 
and love them, we also have a product owner,  

191
00:15:32,440 --> 00:15:38,800
then we have a Scrum master, and the Scrum master 
is in charge in Scrum of actually helping people  

192
00:15:38,800 --> 00:15:43,640
do Scrum better. That's literally their job. How 
do I do Scrum better? How do I make sure that the  

193
00:15:43,640 --> 00:15:48,600
team is working well together? They host things 
like retrospectives where at the end of a sprint  

194
00:15:48,600 --> 00:15:54,040
we say what went well, what didn't go well, how 
should we actually inspect and adapt our process.  

195
00:15:54,040 --> 00:15:59,600
The product owner is where things get murky.
The product owner in general first showed up with  

196
00:15:59,600 --> 00:16:04,760
Scrum, and if you go and you read the first Scrum 
guide, which I pulled up and started reading,  

197
00:16:04,760 --> 00:16:10,800
because I've been very fascinated about how 
this is described, it says that the product  

198
00:16:10,800 --> 00:16:16,440
owner is responsible for maximizing the value of 
work done, the team does the work. Interesting,  

199
00:16:16,440 --> 00:16:20,200
because now the product owner is not quite 
part of the team. The team consists of  

200
00:16:20,200 --> 00:16:24,160
developers with all the skills to turn the 
product owner's request into the potentially  

201
00:16:24,160 --> 00:16:28,920
shippable increment each sprint. The team 
is usually seven plus or minus two members. 

202
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:34,640
Then when you go further into the first version 
of the Scrum Guide, it does say that the Scrum  

203
00:16:34,640 --> 00:16:39,520
master works with the customers and management 
to identify and instantiate a product owner.  

204
00:16:39,520 --> 00:16:43,920
The Scrum master teaches the product owner how 
to do his or her job in order to optimize the  

205
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:49,160
value of the use of Scrum. If they don't, 
the Scrum master is held accountable. Then  

206
00:16:49,160 --> 00:16:53,000
it's got another tip if we go deeper into 
this. It says per commercial development,  

207
00:16:53,000 --> 00:16:57,400
the product owner may be the product manager. 
For in-house development efforts, the product  

208
00:16:57,400 --> 00:17:03,720
owner could be the user department manager.
What's interesting is that that was the first  

209
00:17:03,720 --> 00:17:07,560
version of the Scrum Guide, and I get into 
arguments about the Scrum Guide with people  

210
00:17:07,560 --> 00:17:12,880
all the time. 2013's version though, the more 
updated one that you could go and find is the  

211
00:17:12,880 --> 00:17:18,440
one that almost every company has run an agile 
transformation off of. It loses that thing that  

212
00:17:18,440 --> 00:17:23,280
says the product manager could be the product 
owner. It doesn't say it anywhere in that guide.  

213
00:17:23,280 --> 00:17:28,200
This was the first version, and you can kind of 
tell it was an aside. It's like, "Oh, by the way,  

214
00:17:28,200 --> 00:17:31,480
the product owner in Scrum doesn't need to be 
a product manager, it could be the customer, it  

215
00:17:31,480 --> 00:17:37,240
could be a developer." It's usually the customer.
When they were writing this too, sometimes the  

216
00:17:37,240 --> 00:17:42,400
customer was an internal person at a bank or 
somewhere where we were building software who  

217
00:17:42,400 --> 00:17:48,200
was asking for the software. They were like, "Go 
build me an internal tool. Go do this." Now we're  

218
00:17:48,200 --> 00:17:54,080
just asking for requirements inside a company, 
and that's where you can start to see how the  

219
00:17:54,080 --> 00:17:59,200
product owner role kind of evolved into somebody 
going to ask, "Hey, what do you want me to build?  

220
00:17:59,200 --> 00:18:03,960
What's required here?," and then just listening to 
somebody come back and say, "I need this feature,  

221
00:18:03,960 --> 00:18:09,960
I need this feature, I need this feature." Scrum 
doesn't describe how to get the stuff into the  

222
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:17,160
backlog, and it didn't in the 2013 manuals. 
The manuals have all been a little bit better,  

223
00:18:17,160 --> 00:18:21,920
they've all kind of been updated since then, and 
they do describe it has to start with the vision  

224
00:18:21,920 --> 00:18:25,680
a little bit more, you have to break down the 
vision for the product and get in there, but none  

225
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:31,520
of that existed in the early versions of Scrum.
When people got trained on how to be a product  

226
00:18:31,520 --> 00:18:37,360
owner, what was happening here is, and this is 
the whole other world of Scrum over here, when  

227
00:18:37,360 --> 00:18:42,280
people get trained to be a product owner, it's 
usually a two-day class where they teach them,  

228
00:18:42,280 --> 00:18:46,760
"Hey, this is how you break down a backlog. 
This is how you do stand-ups with your teams.  

229
00:18:46,760 --> 00:18:50,400
This is how you think about prioritizing 
work. This is how you manage your backlog,  

230
00:18:50,400 --> 00:18:55,680
prioritize it for the developers. This is how 
you work with the retrospectives," but it doesn't  

231
00:18:55,680 --> 00:19:00,360
teach them about experimentation, it doesn't teach 
them about market research, it doesn't teach them  

232
00:19:00,360 --> 00:19:06,760
about data, it doesn't teach them about any of 
the things that we need to be a product manager. 

233
00:19:06,760 --> 00:19:15,160
Then what happened was we went into these agile 
transformations at these companies and they said,  

234
00:19:15,160 --> 00:19:21,280
"Hey, let's adopt Scrum because Scrum was built 
as a way to build better products faster." It's  

235
00:19:21,280 --> 00:19:26,560
literally the tagline. Everybody was like, "Yeah, 
I want to build products faster. Okay, great.  

236
00:19:26,560 --> 00:19:32,480
Let's do Scrum." All these large organizations 
back in the early 2010s, in the 2000s said, "Oh,  

237
00:19:32,480 --> 00:19:36,520
we got to be better at software. How do we do 
this better? Otherwise, we're going to lose  

238
00:19:36,520 --> 00:19:42,440
when it comes to innovation." They adopted 
Scrum as a way to build software faster. 

239
00:19:42,440 --> 00:19:49,280
Now, what happened is in order to do Scrum, Scrum 
basically sells training. That's what Scrum does.  

240
00:19:49,280 --> 00:19:54,640
All of these agile coaches would come in and teach 
the product owners, newly minted product owners,  

241
00:19:54,640 --> 00:19:58,400
took all those people, made them into product 
owners, put them through a two-day class and  

242
00:19:58,400 --> 00:20:02,880
then say, "Go." That was the beginning of 
all the agile transformations, and that's  

243
00:20:02,880 --> 00:20:08,560
where a lot of companies still are today. This 
product owner role did not emerge from product  

244
00:20:08,560 --> 00:20:15,840
management as we know it today, it was a way to 
help the developers prioritize what to work on,  

245
00:20:15,840 --> 00:20:20,520
but that was it. The product owner was 
held accountable for making sure that they  

246
00:20:20,520 --> 00:20:26,760
were working on the most pressing things or the 
highest value things, they do say that, but to me,  

247
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:30,680
if you look at it from a developer perspective, 
it's also the person where you can say, "Hey,  

248
00:20:30,680 --> 00:20:35,360
well, you told me to build that, right? We didn't 
build it wrong. You told me to build that." 

249
00:20:35,360 --> 00:20:39,280
It almost gets into consulting territory 
where you're like, "Okay. If the product  

250
00:20:39,280 --> 00:20:44,720
owner prioritized all this stuff for me and told 
me what to do, I can't be held accountable if it  

251
00:20:44,720 --> 00:20:50,440
was the wrong thing to build." Some of that stuff 
does come up in a lot of teams that struggle to  

252
00:20:50,440 --> 00:20:57,320
adopt agile, to adopt Scrum. I feel like there's 
a big misunderstanding out there about what is  

253
00:20:57,320 --> 00:21:04,400
this role and what should we be doing, but the 
premise of this is when we talk about Scrum,  

254
00:21:04,400 --> 00:21:08,520
it's just one piece of the puzzle, 
and when people talk about agile now,  

255
00:21:08,520 --> 00:21:12,720
they almost always associate it with Scrum.
I was actually Googling agile methodologies,  

256
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:18,480
and like I said, the other ones, Kanbans is an 
agile methodology, XP is an agile methodology.  

257
00:21:18,480 --> 00:21:23,280
They don't have product owners, they do not exist 
in those methodologies. There are four developers  

258
00:21:23,280 --> 00:21:30,360
to work on things, or teams to work on things. 
XP would consider product managers in the teams  

259
00:21:30,360 --> 00:21:37,360
as far as I know it, but Scrum kind of sees 
it as a separate thing. Agile methodologies,  

260
00:21:37,360 --> 00:21:41,320
everybody says, "Oh, they're Scrum now," so it 
gets a bad connotation out there about what to  

261
00:21:41,320 --> 00:21:46,920
do with it. I think Scrum if you do it well is 
bad, but you have to understand that it's just  

262
00:21:46,920 --> 00:21:52,920
one piece of building great products, it's not 
the whole thing, and companies will adopt it like  

263
00:21:52,920 --> 00:21:58,920
it's going to radically transform everything. To 
be fair, a lot of times it's sold that way too.

264
00:21:58,920 --> 00:22:03,720
There's a bigger picture question that's coming 
to mind as you talk about this. I'm imagining  

265
00:22:03,720 --> 00:22:07,720
founders listening to this and smaller companies 
listening to this be like, "Why do we need any  

266
00:22:07,720 --> 00:22:14,080
of this?", especially Silicon Valley startups, 
"We're just going to build stuff. We don't need  

267
00:22:14,080 --> 00:22:19,400
these frameworks, we don't need a Scrum master. We 
just have awesome developers and product managers  

268
00:22:19,400 --> 00:22:23,200
and we're just going to build awesome stuff." I 
don't know anyone that has worked this way that  

269
00:22:23,200 --> 00:22:29,960
has built amazing things. Can you talk a bit 
about who ends up looking for solutions here,  

270
00:22:29,960 --> 00:22:36,480
where this even comes from, what companies need 
help here versus, "I just don't need any of this?"

271
00:22:36,480 --> 00:22:39,800
A lot of large companies turn 
to Scrum or to the frameworks,  

272
00:22:39,800 --> 00:22:44,880
and it's because they traditionally didn't grow 
up building software. They're looking at how do  

273
00:22:44,880 --> 00:22:49,760
I implement something that has rigor at scale, and 
that's where you see a lot of Scrum come up. Now,  

274
00:22:49,760 --> 00:22:55,640
I've seen startups using Scrum. Some of them 
do it fine, they understand that it's just more  

275
00:22:55,640 --> 00:22:59,960
about trying to get things out the door every 
two weeks to test it with customers. I think  

276
00:22:59,960 --> 00:23:04,720
if you keep that philosophy, like I said, I used 
it and we didn't have a lot of rigor around it,  

277
00:23:04,720 --> 00:23:09,680
that was fine. When we were doing Scrum, when I 
did it with my team back in OpenSky, we got to  

278
00:23:09,680 --> 00:23:12,840
this point where we were like, "Two weeks is too 
