00:23:17,280 --> 00:23:21,440
but we kipped daily stand-ups. We didn't need 
to stand around and talk about it, we talked to  

281
00:23:21,440 --> 00:23:27,720
each other every day. For me, what was amazing and 
where I see teams actually thrive when they start  

282
00:23:27,720 --> 00:23:32,400
using Scrum is when you go and talk to people. 
You're having the conversations about the work,  

283
00:23:32,400 --> 00:23:36,600
you're breaking it down, you're understanding 
it, so the developers and the rest of the team  

284
00:23:36,600 --> 00:23:41,520
can go hit the road running and people can ask 
important questions. If you're not doing that,  

285
00:23:41,520 --> 00:23:45,360
that's where I think things like a framework 
help, but if you already are doing that,  

286
00:23:45,360 --> 00:23:49,600
you don't need a framework, you don't need 
Scrum, you don't need to be prescribed to  

287
00:23:49,600 --> 00:23:54,840
this two-week sprint or anything like that.
As long as you have a methodology, it doesn't  

288
00:23:54,840 --> 00:23:59,120
even have to be a defined methodology. As long 
as you have a way of working that gets things  

289
00:23:59,120 --> 00:24:05,920
out to customers, well, who cares? Who actually 
cares? Where there's a lot of, I think, baggage  

290
00:24:05,920 --> 00:24:10,840
in the industry and where I hear product managers 
get really frustrated and other people as well,  

291
00:24:10,840 --> 00:24:16,720
developers too, is that when you do Scrum by 
the book or how people teach it and how they  

292
00:24:16,720 --> 00:24:21,800
write about it, it's a million meetings. I know 
they were put in there so that people were forced  

293
00:24:21,800 --> 00:24:26,480
to talk, but when you already know what you're 
