00:29:41,080 --> 00:29:47,040
where all these product owners were just basically 
trying to keep these backlogs full for developers,  

359
00:29:47,040 --> 00:29:52,720
and they were working on such a narrow level. When 
a lot of organizations too I saw it reorganized  

360
00:29:52,720 --> 00:29:57,600
into agile teams, they did it by component. 
Everybody was over every tiny little feature,  

361
00:29:57,600 --> 00:30:03,800
and these teams were massive, super huge scope, 
and some of the stuff was just not prioritized.  

362
00:30:03,800 --> 00:30:08,080
It was done, you didn't need to work on it. They 
were finding work to do so people wouldn't get  

363
00:30:08,080 --> 00:30:13,200
fired. That's how the product owners operated. 
There was all this legacy baggage sometimes in  

364
00:30:13,200 --> 00:30:20,920
companies where they were all re-put on things by 
component, and they're just making up work to do. 

365
00:30:20,920 --> 00:30:25,680
SAFe introduced this kind of split between product 
manager and product owner, and if you look at the  

366
00:30:25,680 --> 00:30:31,720
map, the product owner is part of the agile 
team where they sit with the Scrum masters,  

367
00:30:31,720 --> 00:30:35,800
which is a team coach that they call here 
and the developers, and then the product  

368
00:30:35,800 --> 00:30:41,160
manager is sitting with a system architect and 
what they call a release train engineer. What  

369
00:30:41,160 --> 00:30:48,200
SAFe does is they pull a bunch of agile teams 
into a release train and you get on the train  

370
00:30:48,200 --> 00:30:53,040
when you're ready to ship things and you make 
sure that it all goes pretty smoothly to get  

371
00:30:53,040 --> 00:30:58,240
to that potential shippable increment or that big 
feature launch that you would be doing with SAFe. 

372
00:30:58,240 --> 00:31:02,720
SAFe's really good at prescribing how to do that, 
they're great at describing how to do the release  

373
00:31:02,720 --> 00:31:07,320
trains, how to bring those teams together, how to 
put them on it. Then they do this thing called big  

374
00:31:07,320 --> 00:31:12,120
room planning where they get the entire release 
train together, all these teams, they put them in  

375
00:31:12,120 --> 00:31:16,800
a room and in every quarter you're breaking down 
what we're all going to work on. Where I hear  

376
00:31:16,800 --> 00:31:21,720
frustration from teams every time I come in and 
train them is that when you do big room planning,  

377
00:31:21,720 --> 00:31:27,280
a lot of times it's a commitment. You start at the 
quarter, they haven't been doing good discovery  

378
00:31:27,280 --> 00:31:30,720
because remember, these people have not been 
trained on good discovery so they don't really  

379
00:31:30,720 --> 00:31:36,280
know what they should be working on, they haven't 
been out talking to customers a lot of times. They  

380
00:31:36,280 --> 00:31:40,040
kind of scramble, they figure out what needs to 
happen. Usually they have a backlog of stuff that  

381
00:31:40,040 --> 00:31:44,760
does need to happen, it just has to get done. 
They map it all out in a big room together,  

382
00:31:44,760 --> 00:31:50,360
they commit to it, and then that's the quarter.
They ask me, "When am I supposed to do discovery?"  

383
00:31:50,360 --> 00:31:54,360
I'm like, "Well before that ideally you should 
have a vision. You should be breaking it down,  

384
00:31:54,360 --> 00:31:57,840
you should be putting discovery into that vision, 
talking to customers, feeding that in there."  

385
00:31:58,800 --> 00:32:03,960
Then I hear, "We don't have time to do that 
because we sprint back to back." I was like,  

386
00:32:03,960 --> 00:32:10,680
"What does that mean?", and they're like, "As 
a team, we go and we basically do two-week  

387
00:32:10,680 --> 00:32:15,200
sprint into two-week sprint into two-week sprint, 
and I got to make sure my developers are full. I  

388
00:32:15,200 --> 00:32:19,320
got to make sure they have things to work on. 
If I go take time off to go talk to customers,  

389
00:32:19,320 --> 00:32:23,760
which also is not my job as a product owner, it's 
my product manager's job, they'll feed me in what  

390
00:32:23,760 --> 00:32:27,520
the customers are saying, then I break those down 
into features and I can work with the developers  

391
00:32:27,520 --> 00:32:34,800
on it." That's how all of this stuff starts going.
What happens in organizations that they don't  

392
00:32:34,800 --> 00:32:42,440
understand here is that it's not the most 
efficient way to work. I see a lot of developers  

393
00:32:42,440 --> 00:32:50,800
out there become almost ... How do you describe 
it? Reliant on the product manager or product  

394
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:55,240
owner to tell them what to do. Even though you 
build them this great vision and you explain what  

395
00:32:55,240 --> 00:33:01,480
needs to happen, they go, "Oh, I can't work on it 
because the product owner hasn't prioritized it."  

396
00:33:02,000 --> 00:33:05,440
Then they asked me, "If I don't have enough 
for the developers to do on feature work,  

397
00:33:05,440 --> 00:33:09,080
what are they supposed to do?" I said, "I 
guarantee you there's a ton of tech debt  

398
00:33:09,080 --> 00:33:13,000
they could be working on. You don't have 
to scope that out. Let them choose what's  

399
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:16,400
the most important thing. They should be working 
together as developers and architects to figure  

400
00:33:16,400 --> 00:33:21,040
out how to tackle some of that tech debt, 
how to get into it while you're figuring out  

401
00:33:21,040 --> 00:33:26,520
is this the right thing to be building."
With all of this stuff, people feel like  

402
00:33:26,520 --> 00:33:29,760
they don't have time because they're in a 
million meetings, and the expectations of  

403
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:34,040
these companies is that every sprint, we're 
delivering software towards these roadmaps  

404
00:33:34,040 --> 00:33:39,040
that we promised in the last quarter and 
we're not checking to see if they're right,  

405
00:33:39,040 --> 00:33:43,600
we're not checking to see if they're actually 
helping us move it forward, and a lot of times  

406
00:33:43,600 --> 00:33:48,120
the organizations are not set up with the right 
feedback mechanisms, the right user research and  

407
00:33:48,120 --> 00:33:53,000
the right data to tell us if everything is 
working so they can feed that in to the next  

408
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:57,720
release planning. They're just planning, planning, 
planning, breaking it down into sprints and going. 

409
00:33:58,600 --> 00:34:06,040
SAFe is not good at describing how you do all 
that other work. In a lot of this stuff too,  

410
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:11,920
there's pieces that they put onto this map of 
SAFe where they're like, "Hey, you should do  

411
00:34:11,920 --> 00:34:17,760
OKRs," and it's like, "This is what OKRs are. You 
should do a roadmap. This is what a roadmap is."  

412
00:34:17,760 --> 00:34:22,560
How all of that cycle works together where you're 
balancing discovery and delivery and feeding it in  

413
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:27,280
is really confusing in organizations. Then 
what it's basically saying is a lot of the  

414
00:34:27,280 --> 00:34:31,160
discovery work goes into the product managers, 
and the product managers, the product owners  

415
00:34:31,160 --> 00:34:37,800
report into the product managers. What I've seen 
that doesn't work here is that you're basically  

416
00:34:37,800 --> 00:34:43,480
making these product owners order-takers. They 
are extremely tactical, and then when it's  

417
00:34:43,480 --> 00:34:47,400
time to actually be more strategic, let's say 
you want to be promoted to a product manager,  

418
00:34:47,400 --> 00:34:52,800
some organizations, that's not even the same 
business line, not even the same career path. It's  

419
00:34:52,800 --> 00:34:57,200
product owners go over here and product managers 
go here and they report into different people. 

420
00:34:58,040 --> 00:35:01,320
If you ever want to move from product owner 
to product manager, a lot of times you don't  

421
00:35:01,320 --> 00:35:05,680
get experience with the strategy, figuring 
out what customers want, breaking it down,  

422
00:35:05,680 --> 00:35:09,320
looking at the market research, determining 
is this valuable, is this what we should be  

423
00:35:09,320 --> 00:35:14,240
working on. They're not even getting exposure 
or a chance to do that because SAFe is like,  

424
00:35:14,240 --> 00:35:21,040
"No, that's the product manager's job. Your job is 
to go really deep and work with the developers."

425
00:35:21,040 --> 00:35:28,600
Wow, okay. A lot of this sounds quite absurd as 
someone hearing all of the details and looking at  

426
00:35:28,600 --> 00:35:36,040
this image. That being said, many companies are 
adopting this. It feels like it's growing. More  

427
00:35:36,040 --> 00:35:42,280
and more companies are adopting this as the way 
to work. I imagine the incentive is we just want  

428
00:35:42,280 --> 00:35:47,440
to build great software and we don't know exactly 
how, and there's this process we can plug in and  

429
00:35:47,440 --> 00:35:55,200
it'll help us do it. I guess thoughts on that, 
and do you find it can work or often works or  

430
00:35:55,200 --> 00:35:59,760
often doesn't work? What is your experience 
with people adopting this and how it goes?

431
00:35:59,760 --> 00:36:04,640
I know a ton of companies that adopted SAFe 
about eight years ago and have gotten rid of  

432
00:36:04,640 --> 00:36:09,600
it. Capital One just came out and said they 
got rid of all their agile roles, all their  

433
00:36:09,600 --> 00:36:15,160
Scrum roles. They were early adopter of SAFe, they 
don't do it anymore. They wrote about that in the  

434
00:36:15,160 --> 00:36:22,000
newspaper. I've seen it happen more often. Now, in 
a lot of our organizations too I'll see parts of  

435
00:36:22,000 --> 00:36:27,560
them do SAFe and other parts not do SAFe. It 
could change business line to business line.  

436
00:36:28,640 --> 00:36:35,120
I don't think though that people grasp how much 
it's still out there. I get questions on SAFe  

437
00:36:35,120 --> 00:36:40,280
every single day on the podcast. Everybody asks 
me, "Why are we still doing this?" It's for what  

438
00:36:40,280 --> 00:36:46,800
you said, executives buy SAFe because it's the 
only framework out there that basically draws  

439
00:36:46,800 --> 00:36:52,680
them a map and says, "Plug and play, do this."
That's why everybody's so excited about it because  

440
00:36:52,680 --> 00:36:57,840
it's the only thing that specifies things to this 
level, and they went, "Oh, it's something I can  

441
00:36:57,840 --> 00:37:01,440
understand, it's something that actually 
has definitions around it." To be fair,  

442
00:37:01,440 --> 00:37:05,960
that was a great thing for SAFe 
to do as a marketing tool. Bravo,  

443
00:37:05,960 --> 00:37:11,880
they created this thing that everybody wants, 
a good product to sell, but it's overkill,  

444
00:37:11,880 --> 00:37:17,120
and that's what I keep hearing from organizations 
is it's basically taking the responsibility away  

445
00:37:17,120 --> 00:37:22,920
from leaders to go figure their stuff out 
themselves as well. If you are a new leader  

446
00:37:22,920 --> 00:37:27,520
and you've just been dropped into this role, 
I have tremendous empathy for them because  

447
00:37:28,240 --> 00:37:32,760
yeah, where do you get started? How do 
you try to run a technology organization? 

448
00:37:33,520 --> 00:37:38,400
Somebody came and told me, the CIO came and told 
me I'm in charge now. I'm in charge of all of the  

449
00:37:38,400 --> 00:37:44,520
developers, or I'm in charge of all the product 
managers. Now, where do you start? I can totally  

450
00:37:44,520 --> 00:37:49,440
tell why people adopt SAFe because you're like, 
"Oh, I've been looking for the handbook. I've been  

451
00:37:49,440 --> 00:37:55,640
looking for something to do here." The problem 
is it's only solving a little bit of the puzzle,  

452
00:37:55,640 --> 00:37:59,800
which is bringing those teams together. 
People do say it does really strains well,  

453
00:37:59,800 --> 00:38:04,520
but it doesn't tell you also how to do your job 
as a leader, it leaves it all out. They talk about  

454
00:38:04,520 --> 00:38:08,760
portfolio visions and portfolio management 
and SAFe there too, but more often than not,  

455
00:38:08,760 --> 00:38:13,040
I come in and I find everybody above product 
owners and product managers, let's talk about  

456
00:38:13,040 --> 00:38:17,840
directors of product, VPs of product, they don't 
know what they should be doing as a VP of product  

457
00:38:17,840 --> 00:38:23,320
or a director of product. It's like, "What's 
my role? What should I be feeding in here?" 

458
00:38:23,320 --> 00:38:27,600
SAFe doesn't even have that in there, that's not 
even a role. Product manager going up into those  

459
00:38:27,600 --> 00:38:34,040
levels is not really there. What do you 
do when you own a whole product line in  

460
00:38:34,040 --> 00:38:38,320
an organization? What you do when you're the 
head of product for a credit card at a bank,  

461
00:38:38,320 --> 00:38:45,160
right? What's my job? Doesn't say that. There's 
a lot of people out there in these organizations  

462
00:38:45,160 --> 00:38:49,160
that I've been working with who I'm like, 
"You are supposed to be doing strategy,  

463
00:38:49,160 --> 00:38:53,920
and this is how you do strategy. This is how you 
go out and talk to customers. This is the patterns  

464
00:38:53,920 --> 00:39:00,040
that we have in software. Are you doing a platform 
strategy? Do you need APIs? How do you think about  

465
00:39:00,040 --> 00:39:06,120
your app strategy, rolling it out? How do you do 
this here?" All of that stuff doesn't quite come  

466
00:39:06,120 --> 00:39:12,800
from ways of working, which is what SAFe is doing. 
It's about how do you do your jobs in those areas? 

467
00:39:12,800 --> 00:39:17,560
A lot of organizations who adopt SAFe don't 
realize that you need a head of product, you  

468
00:39:17,560 --> 00:39:22,480
need somebody to actually be feeding that vision 
all the way down and make sure it's breaking up  

469
00:39:22,480 --> 00:39:27,080
around the teams and controlling that portfolio 
vision and doing all of these things into it.  

470
00:39:28,280 --> 00:39:33,280
I have not seen SAFe slowing down by any 
means out there for people adopting it,  

471
00:39:33,280 --> 00:39:39,080
I see more and more organizations adopting 
it. I think we take for granted too in Silicon  

472
00:39:39,080 --> 00:39:45,360
Valley how many people are just starting on 
their journey for digital transformation.  

473
00:39:45,360 --> 00:39:50,960
There's a lot of pharmaceutical companies, 
banks, insurance companies, they outsource  

474
00:39:50,960 --> 00:39:55,720
their development or they had an IT team, but 
they never had to really think about it before  

475
00:39:55,720 --> 00:40:01,920
because digital wasn't as important. Now they do.
Some of these companies, most of these companies  

476
00:40:01,920 --> 00:40:07,720
are Fortune 50 companies, right? Fortune 100 
companies. I think a lot of the ones I see,  

477
00:40:07,720 --> 00:40:13,240
at least banks, realized early on, "Hey, when 
it comes to apps and how people interact with  

478
00:40:13,800 --> 00:40:18,680
our stuff, software is important," but there's 
a lot of companies that did not catch that train  

479
00:40:18,680 --> 00:40:22,720
and they're just starting, and then they 
turn to things like SAFe because it gives  

480
00:40:22,720 --> 00:40:27,600
them a guideline. "Hey, I've never done this 
before. I've been in this bank for 40 years.  

481
00:40:27,600 --> 00:40:33,800
All I know is waterfall type development. What do 
we do?" Then we'll go, "We'll go look at SAFe."

482
00:40:33,800 --> 00:40:38,240
I love that we spend time on that because I think 
it's really important. You can be cynical about  

483
00:40:38,240 --> 00:40:43,400
all this and be like, "What the hell are people 
thinking? This is crazy," but as you described,  

484
00:40:43,400 --> 00:40:48,080
people just have a problem to solve, they've 
never done this before, they look for solutions,  

485
00:40:48,080 --> 00:40:51,080
they find something that seems right, they see 
other people doing this and like, "Okay, let's  

486
00:40:51,080 --> 00:40:57,240
try this thing." What you've seen is it rarely 
actually works out the SAFe specific approach. 

487
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:05,040
There's a few ways I think we can help folks. 
One is someone trying to do say an agile  

488
00:41:05,040 --> 00:41:10,080
transformation or a digital transformation, your 
advice for how to actually do that better. Then  

489
00:41:10,080 --> 00:41:14,320
I want to talk about say you're a product owner 
or a PM within an organization that works like  

490
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:18,400
this. What can you do? Maybe let's start with 
the first. Say someone's trying to figure out,  

491
00:41:19,160 --> 00:41:23,760
"We need to build better products. Something's 
not working right." SAFe is an option. Your  

492
00:41:23,760 --> 00:41:28,040
suggestion is don't maybe do that. What 
should people do? I know you're not going  

493
00:41:28,040 --> 00:41:33,680
to have the answer in a short answer, but 
generally, how should people approach this?

494
00:41:33,680 --> 00:41:38,480
Yeah. When I've worked with companies 
on digital transformations, you want a  

495
00:41:38,480 --> 00:41:43,440
development operating model. That's where a lot 
of these agile methodologies came out of. You  

496
00:41:43,440 --> 00:41:46,520
have to understand that's just the development 
operating model, that's not actually going to  

497
00:41:46,520 --> 00:41:51,200
help you with go-to-market, with launching your 
products and with product management. What I  

498
00:41:51,200 --> 00:41:56,840
advise for companies to do is first sit down 
and say, "Hey, how do we think about building  

499
00:41:56,840 --> 00:42:03,920
our operating model?" When I think of product 
operating models and what I do with companies  

500
00:42:03,920 --> 00:42:08,680
is we break out how do you determine product 
strategy? Do you have a good product strategy?  

501
00:42:08,680 --> 00:42:14,000
You look at your organizational design. 
How are we actually organized around our  

502
00:42:14,000 --> 00:42:17,680
products? Do we have good coverage of 
product managers and do we have skilled  

503
00:42:17,680 --> 00:42:22,760
product managers up and down the organization?
Then we want to look at product operations. Do  

504
00:42:22,760 --> 00:42:26,400
we have the infrastructure in there to help 
support these teams? Can they get the data  

505
00:42:26,400 --> 00:42:31,760
to make decisions? Can they actually be in touch 
with customers? A lot of these large organizations  

506
00:42:31,760 --> 00:42:36,960
haven't actually thought through many of those 
steps as well that enable product managers and  

507
00:42:36,960 --> 00:42:42,480
development teams to be successful. They don't 
have ways for them to go and talk to customers.  

508
00:42:42,480 --> 00:42:47,840
That's why they're not doing it. I have a lot of 
empathy for people in these organizations as well  

509
00:42:47,840 --> 00:42:53,400
who can't do product management well because of 
the bureaucracy or the things around it. Leaders  

510
00:42:53,400 --> 00:42:57,120
need to solve that, right? They need to understand 
what the role is and they need to open it up. 

511
00:42:57,680 --> 00:43:03,120
Then we got to look at our culture and incentives. 
Are we just rewarding people for shipping as many  

512
00:43:03,120 --> 00:43:08,200
things as possible, which is like, "Hey, just 
put everything you possibly can into that release  

513
00:43:08,200 --> 00:43:14,760
train or that backlog," or are we coming back and 
saying, "Hey, is this valuable? Is this tying it  

514
00:43:14,760 --> 00:43:21,480
back to our business?" Many organizations 
do not have a great product strategy,  

515
00:43:21,480 --> 00:43:27,520
many large organizations that I've worked with, 
and it's that tying it back to the value piece,  

516
00:43:27,520 --> 00:43:31,760
tying it back to, is this going to reach our 
company goals? If you are a huge organization  

517
00:43:31,760 --> 00:43:37,880
and let's say making billions of dollars a 
year, and your goal is expand geographically,  

518
00:43:37,880 --> 00:43:43,080
what are you doing in your portfolio to actually 
enable that? What products are you building to  

519
00:43:43,080 --> 00:43:50,560
expand geographically? So many organizations don't 
have the transparency to actually even see that. 

520
00:43:50,560 --> 00:43:56,480
One crazy thing, a lot of people give large 
organizations a lot of flack for, and I know Marty  

521
00:43:56,480 --> 00:44:02,240
does this too, for focusing on processes. I don't 
think processes are the enemy here. For example,  

522
00:44:02,240 --> 00:44:06,560
if I hear somebody really worried about getting a 
roadmapping tool in there or something like that,  

523
00:44:06,560 --> 00:44:12,000
I'm like, "Yes, you need that because you have 
no idea what your 4,000 teams are doing." If  

524
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:16,280
they're actually coming back to the business 
goals, you have no infrastructure in there  

525
00:44:16,280 --> 00:44:20,160
to be able to see that transparency. 
Those types of blocking tackling is  

526
00:44:20,160 --> 00:44:25,320
absolutely necessary for a transformation 
for a organization to be stood up around  

527
00:44:25,320 --> 00:44:29,000
software product management. You have to have 
the transparency to actually see those things. 

528
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:35,680
You do need to have enough process so that you as 
an organization can be efficient in getting things  

529
00:44:35,680 --> 00:44:40,800
out the door, and that's what I think SAFe was 
trying to do, but it's not working because it's  

530
00:44:40,800 --> 00:44:45,080
not solving the problems of the product management 
and it's not solving that problem of connecting  

531
00:44:45,080 --> 00:44:53,920
the value back to the product teams. Instead, it's 
seen as a role that almost babysits developers or  

532
00:44:53,920 --> 00:44:58,840
tells everybody what to do. Where's the discovery? 
Where do those things come in? I know with the  

533
00:44:58,840 --> 00:45:04,440
SAFe image that we got over here, they try to drop 
things like Lean UX in there, which Jeff Gothelf  

534
00:45:04,440 --> 00:45:08,960
thinks it's hilarious, but it's not really pulling 
it all together of how do we do this on a cadence?  

535
00:45:09,920 --> 00:45:14,920
How do we help people go out there and actually 
talk to customers? How do we enable them to do it? 

536
00:45:14,920 --> 00:45:20,360
If you're starting a transformation, it's not 
just thinking about how do we build the product,  

537
00:45:20,360 --> 00:45:23,280
but you should also be thinking about how do we 
launch the product and how do we make sure this  

538
00:45:23,280 --> 00:45:29,160
is the right product to do. That's the big pieces 
of it, and that's where all that product strategy  

539
00:45:29,160 --> 00:45:37,160
comes in. You should also look at the career 
paths. This is what really bothers me about agile  

540
00:45:37,160 --> 00:45:43,960
transformations and what bothers me with Scrum 
and SAFe is that when we organized in these large  

541
00:45:43,960 --> 00:45:50,640
organizations into agile teams, we made all these 
new roles called a product owner, and so many  

542
00:45:50,640 --> 00:45:56,560
organizations don't have a career path for them so 
they email me and they go, "What's my career path?  

543
00:45:56,560 --> 00:46:02,440
What do I do next? Where am I supposed to go?"
I've been saying for 10 years, this is not a team  

544
00:46:02,440 --> 00:46:08,600
role, it's not just a team role, it's a business 
role and it rolls all the way up to helping you  

545
00:46:08,600 --> 00:46:14,720
further your business. You have to make sure 
that people on teams can be promoted to running  

546
00:46:14,720 --> 00:46:20,720
multiple teams, can be promoted to running an 
entire product line. To us, that's so simple  

547
00:46:20,720 --> 00:46:27,200
in Silicon Valley native software companies, but 
it's still unheard of in other organizations. What  

548
00:46:27,200 --> 00:46:33,520
happens too, and this is where I think leadership 
and C-suite needs to really pay attention,  

549
00:46:33,520 --> 00:46:38,600
because we're transforming in this way of working, 
what happens is some of the roles that we had  

550
00:46:38,600 --> 00:46:44,880
before do not serve us now. Maybe we don't need 
a million project managers, maybe people in the  

551
00:46:44,880 --> 00:46:50,000
business who decided what we're going to build, 
are they the right people to bring with us on  

552
00:46:50,000 --> 00:46:55,920
this next phase into product management? Can they 
learn? Can they grok software? Do they understand  

553
00:46:55,920 --> 00:47:00,800
those pieces? That's what we have to ask.
Organizations are so afraid sometimes to  

554
00:47:00,800 --> 00:47:05,920
put these career ladders in because it kind of 
overhauls their traditional ways of working,  

555
00:47:05,920 --> 00:47:10,400
and then they've got people who've been in these 
organizations for 40 years and now you're saying,  

556
00:47:10,400 --> 00:47:14,880
"Hey, you're actually not in charge of that, the 
product manager is in charge of that," and that's  

557
00:47:14,880 --> 00:47:20,000
scary. A lot of them get in the way because of 
that. If you really want to transform though,  

558
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:24,160
the C-suite has to be like, "Hey, we're going 
in this direction," and just put it down because  

559
00:47:24,160 --> 00:47:29,040
I've seen it run by a lot of middle managers, a 
transformation run by tons of middle managers,  

560
00:47:29,040 --> 00:47:33,840
and those are the jobs that are usually in 
most jeopardy when you start transforming  

561
00:47:33,840 --> 00:47:37,920
and you have to re-skill and you have to figure 
out what to do, and they don't want to do that.  

562
00:47:37,920 --> 00:47:41,760
They're not going to be the ones who jump 
up and down and say, "Hey, let's do this." 

563
00:47:41,760 --> 00:47:46,680
There's a lot of people out there, I think, 
pushing organizations to try harder and to  

564
00:47:46,680 --> 00:47:50,040
internally as well. I've worked with a lot of 
people who run these transformations who just  

565
00:47:50,040 --> 00:47:55,720
really want it to work, and I think they do it 
with the best of intentions, but the C-suite has  

566
00:47:55,720 --> 00:48:01,920
to understand this is not just a transformation 
project, this is a whole new way of working,  

567
00:48:01,920 --> 00:48:07,040
and if we want a whole new way of working, 
we have to really rise to that occasion.

