621
00:52:44,160 --> 00:52:47,040
There are more people out there and more 
leaders who have done this before because  

622
00:52:47,040 --> 00:52:52,760
we've been doing this for 10 years. There's 
Shruti Patel, she's chief product officer at  

623
00:52:52,760 --> 00:52:58,760
US Bank for small business banking. I just had her 
on the podcast. She worked at Shopify, she saw how  

624
00:52:58,760 --> 00:53:05,240
great teams worked, and then she was able to come 
and help apply that at a bank. She's experienced,  

625
00:53:05,240 --> 00:53:11,000
right? She's an experienced product person who 
comes in to help. Melissa Douros is the CPO of  

626
00:53:11,000 --> 00:53:16,200
Green Dot Bank and she had worked at Discover 
Financial leading the transformation there,  

627
00:53:16,200 --> 00:53:21,760
did all that work, and then could bring it to 
Green Dot Bank. She can see what needs to happen,  

628
00:53:21,760 --> 00:53:24,760
what needs to actually go on here.
We've got more and more people out  

629
00:53:24,760 --> 00:53:28,960
there who have done this before who are looking 
for these opportunities to do it in the bank,  

630
00:53:28,960 --> 00:53:35,240
and I think it's important for C-suite to bring 
them in to actually look at that. Where I've seen  

631
00:53:35,240 --> 00:53:40,680
transformations be the most successful in all 
these organizations is when you do that mix,  

632
00:53:42,400 --> 00:53:47,520
you keep some of your people, but you also 
bring people in to learn. I get hired all  

633
00:53:47,520 --> 00:53:52,320
the time to come in and train. I've worked with 
almost every Fortune 50 company at this point,  

634
00:53:52,320 --> 00:53:56,840
fortune 100 company too, and I get in, I 
come in to train a lot of product managers.  

635
00:53:56,840 --> 00:54:04,120
We do it through Product Institute and we'll train 
everybody. What used to happen about eight years  

636
00:54:04,120 --> 00:54:09,440
ago is they train everybody and they would say, 
"Go." Where do you go after you bring in the  

637
00:54:09,440 --> 00:54:15,720
consultants to do training to keep learning? How 
do they watch other people in the organization do  

638
00:54:15,720 --> 00:54:20,080
great product management if there's nobody 
in the organization who's done it before? 

639
00:54:20,080 --> 00:54:25,360
Luckily I think a lot of organizations are 
realizing that, so more leaders are out there  

640
00:54:25,360 --> 00:54:30,120
who are saying, "Hey, I've got to actually 
intersperse skills here. I need to bring in  

641
00:54:30,120 --> 00:54:33,640
some more directors who are experienced here, some 
more individual contributors who are experienced  

642
00:54:33,640 --> 00:54:39,440
here." Those organizations I think are wildly 
successful because they recognize it and they say,  

643
00:54:39,440 --> 00:54:43,640
"I've got to make sure that people can learn 
from others." That's how you keep developing,  

644
00:54:43,640 --> 00:54:47,720
that's how we all keep developing, it's not 
just doing all external classes. That's where  

645
00:54:47,720 --> 00:54:51,200
I think these things become powerful. You 
could do that at all levels. You don't have  

646
00:54:51,200 --> 00:54:55,400
to just do it with the teams, you could do it 
at director level, you could do it at VP level.  

647
00:54:55,400 --> 00:55:00,320
That's how we should be thinking about this.
Now, there are some CPOs out there and some VPs  

648
00:55:00,320 --> 00:55:06,080
of product in these large organizations who are 
new to this way of working, but they've committed  

649
00:55:06,080 --> 00:55:12,360
themselves to learning and to trying to figure 
out how to do it best. They're not saying, "Hey,  

650
00:55:12,360 --> 00:55:16,440
I'm just going to adopt SAFe or I'm just going 
to do whatever is over here," they're actually  

651
00:55:16,440 --> 00:55:21,520
saying, "What don't I know?" I'm watching them 
go out to talk to other CPOs, do all these other  

652
00:55:21,520 --> 00:55:25,840
things. They usually have great market knowledge, 
