653
00:55:25,840 --> 00:55:30,480
at strategy, and then they hire people underneath 
them who are great at the other pieces like the  

654
00:55:30,480 --> 00:55:35,560
execution and getting the software at the door. 
I think those people are successful in it as well  

655
00:55:35,560 --> 00:55:40,400
because they notice their skill gaps and they 
hire for it just like any great leader would. 

656
00:55:41,320 --> 00:55:48,160
In these organizations, I do see sometimes SAFe 
for something being a crutch for people who don't  

657
00:55:48,160 --> 00:55:54,320
know what they're doing to bring in. If you really 
think about, "Hey, how do I make this better?",  

658
00:55:54,320 --> 00:55:59,680
and have that continuous learning mindset and that 
way to want to propel this forward, I think you'll  

659
00:55:59,680 --> 00:56:04,760
consider other options and start to think about 
broader than just SAFe, broader than just agile,  

660
00:56:04,760 --> 00:56:09,600
what do we need to make this successful?
The key part of this too is recognizing  

661
00:56:09,600 --> 00:56:15,480
that product management is not just this 
role in Scrum. I say this in my talk too,  

662
00:56:15,480 --> 00:56:21,480
I say Take Scrum away. You still need product 
management, right? Product owner doesn't exist  

663
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:26,320
without Scrum, that's not a thing, but you still 
need product managers and that's why all product  

664
00:56:26,320 --> 00:56:31,280
owners should be product managers, they should be 
fundamentally product managers. That's why I do  

665
00:56:31,280 --> 00:56:38,400
not like these career trajectories that keep them 
separate. Sure, if you want to have a principal IC  

666
00:56:38,400 --> 00:56:43,800
product manager like they do in a lot of large 
Silicon Valley companies, perfect, let people  

667
00:56:43,800 --> 00:56:48,200
keep working on those things. They don't have to 
go into management, but that doesn't mean they're  

668
00:56:48,200 --> 00:56:54,960
different. Between an IC product owner and an IC 
product manager, it shouldn't be different there.

669
00:56:54,960 --> 00:56:59,160
Perfect segue to where I wanted to go next, 
which is say you are a product owner today  

670
00:56:59,160 --> 00:57:04,960
listening to this and you're like, "Man, 
this is exactly my life. What can I do?",  

671
00:57:04,960 --> 00:57:09,240
what's your advice to folks in that role right now 
about how to potentially become product managers,  

672
00:57:09,240 --> 00:57:14,480
build the skills they need to not just be stuck 
in this career path that doesn't go anywhere?

673
00:57:14,480 --> 00:57:19,440
Yeah. I think the first thing is bringing 
awareness to that your role is more than  

674
00:57:19,440 --> 00:57:24,240
just working with the developers. A lot of leaders 
argue with me that we need product owners because  

675
00:57:24,240 --> 00:57:30,760
it just doesn't scale. You've seen massive 
companies at scale where they don't have any  

676
00:57:30,760 --> 00:57:35,880
product owners. I do not understand that. It's a 
weak argument to me, it's a very weak argument. It  

677
00:57:35,880 --> 00:57:41,080
just means you don't know how to distribute the 
work evenly and give a little bit of strategic  

678
00:57:41,080 --> 00:57:45,680
guidance to product owners so that they can gon, 
or product managers, on a team so that they can  

679
00:57:45,680 --> 00:57:50,680
go and build visions and cut down features and 
stuff like that. If you're a product owner and  

680
00:57:50,680 --> 00:57:55,200
you're like, "Hey, I don't have the opportunity to 
talk to customers, my product manager does that. I  

681
00:57:55,200 --> 00:58:00,000
am just working with the teams. I want to be more 
strategic, I want to think longer term," I'd say  

682
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:04,760
try to take some ownership over that and push 
back on the things that are being given to you. 

683
00:58:04,760 --> 00:58:08,720
I was doing a workshop for Mind the Product 
back in the day, and I had a product owner  

684
00:58:08,720 --> 00:58:12,880
in my workshop and she said, "I don't think that 
things we're working on," they were doing SAFe,  

685
00:58:12,880 --> 00:58:17,720
"are the right things to work on." I said, "You 
should bring this to your manager," and she was  

686
00:58:17,720 --> 00:58:20,600
like, "I don't know. I'm going to get fired. 
I don't think it's the right thing. What am  

687
00:58:20,600 --> 00:58:24,000
I going to work on if we're not going to work 
on this?" I'm like, "Well, this is the beauty  

688
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:30,320
of product instead of project, we stay with the 
product." Just because your project ends doesn't  

689
00:58:30,320 --> 00:58:34,120
mean that you lose a job. She put together this 
whole thing, went and said, "I don't think we  

690
00:58:34,120 --> 00:58:38,920
should be working on this," and they promoted 
her. They were like, "Fantastic." She took this  

691
00:58:38,920 --> 00:58:44,160
leap of faith and went out there and started 
saying, "This is more. We need to do more." 

692
00:58:44,160 --> 00:58:47,120
I think if you're a product owner 
and there's no career path for you,  

693
00:58:47,120 --> 00:58:52,480
start asking leaders what your career path 
is because it's going to make them go, "Oh,  

694
00:58:52,480 --> 00:58:56,440
great question. What should the career path 
be?" There's a lot of literature out there  

695
00:58:56,440 --> 00:59:01,920
about how we make career paths, so you can start 
there. Ask what's next for you after this product  

696
00:59:01,920 --> 00:59:06,840
owner role. I would ask the product managers 
if they're doing all the customer research,  

697
00:59:06,840 --> 00:59:11,800
see if you can do some customer research with 
them. Go sit in on this. A lot of them will say,  

698
00:59:11,800 --> 00:59:16,240
"I don't have time. I don't have time to do this." 
Strip back all the user stories you're working on,  

699
00:59:16,240 --> 00:59:21,120
stop thinking about it as a quantitative metric 
that needs to just go up and up. Instead,  

700
00:59:21,120 --> 00:59:24,840
really think about the value you're delivering 
with your team. Is this the right thing? 

701
00:59:24,840 --> 00:59:29,280
When you talk to leaders and when you 
present your case, you say it in a way of,  

702
00:59:29,280 --> 00:59:34,520
"Hey, I'm working on X, Y, and Z feature. 
What's the goal here? When we release this,  

703
00:59:34,520 --> 00:59:39,360
what do we hope will happen?" I think that's 
one of the best questions anybody can ask if  

704
00:59:39,360 --> 00:59:42,840
they're worried their company is not 
focused on outcomes. What do we hope  

705
00:59:42,840 --> 00:59:46,240
will happen when we release this? What 
metrics are we going to change? How do  

706
00:59:46,240 --> 00:59:50,160
we instrument it to make sure that's true? 
Then we can go back and actually see if it  

707
00:59:50,160 --> 00:59:55,520
changed. One simple question to get alignment 
on it, and then you can start to say, "Oh,  

708
00:59:55,520 --> 01:00:00,560
that didn't work or this did work." Great. Why 
did it work? You can open up those conversations. 

709
01:00:01,520 --> 01:00:06,800
I'd say there's a lot of things you can do to help 
move your companies forward, and I have seen in a  

710
01:00:06,800 --> 01:00:12,200
lot of these organizations too, a groundswell of 
product owners and product managers saying, "Hey,  

711
01:00:12,920 --> 01:00:19,440
what's next for me? What's going on?" That makes 
the organizations go and figure it out. I was  

712
01:00:19,440 --> 01:00:24,560
working with one Fortune 10 company not too long 
ago, their C-suite, I've been working with them  

713
01:00:24,560 --> 01:00:29,000
for a very long time and they're finally like, 
"Hey, we're going to codify the product manager  

714
01:00:29,000 --> 01:00:32,080
role and we're going to have it all the way up and 
down our organization, we're going to make roles,  

715
01:00:32,080 --> 01:00:36,520
we're going to make responsibilities." To me, that 
was music to my ears, but the reason they were  

716
01:00:36,520 --> 01:00:42,280
doing it too is because they noticed there was 
a lot of churn in the organization in that role,  

717
01:00:42,280 --> 01:00:46,600
and they also realized it's a critical role.
They're losing good people because people from  

718
01:00:46,600 --> 01:00:50,520
the outside are coming because they want to 
work for this great big organization that's  

719
01:00:50,520 --> 01:00:56,400
doing super well, fantastic, but they get in 
there and they go, "Where's my career path?  

720
01:00:56,400 --> 01:01:01,960
What am I supposed to do? Where am I supposed to 
go?" A lot of leaders are out there now realizing,  

721
01:01:01,960 --> 01:01:06,880
"Hey, we do have to get our stuff together," and 
the only reason they're coming to this conclusion  

722
01:01:06,880 --> 01:01:10,600
as well is because they're looking around seeing 
other people doing it and they hear it from the  

723
01:01:10,600 --> 01:01:15,360
teams, they hear it from the product managers. 
I don't want people to think, "Hey, I have no  

724
01:01:15,360 --> 01:01:20,440
power. I'm in a 10,000 person organization." The 
more you bring this up, the more your leaders will  

725
01:01:20,440 --> 01:01:25,080
respect it because they don't want to lose 
you, they don't want to lose good people.  

726
01:01:25,080 --> 01:01:31,280
If you want to be great at your job and you 
need more support there, speak up, speak up. 

727
01:01:31,280 --> 01:01:34,720
At a certain point, I do tell people this. 
If you feel like you can't do great product  

728
01:01:34,720 --> 01:01:40,680
management in your organization, try to find 
another organization. I know that is hard to  

729
01:01:40,680 --> 01:01:47,080
say and I respect people are tied to insurances 
and it's hard to change jobs, but if you do have  

730
01:01:47,080 --> 01:01:52,080
the opportunity to look for another organization 
that does it well, I would go there. I would also  

731
01:01:52,080 --> 01:01:57,760
say in large corporations too, I've seen certain 
business lines and certain divisions do it super  

732
01:01:57,760 --> 01:02:04,080
well and then others not. If you are in a large 
corporation, maybe think about moving internally,  

733
01:02:04,080 --> 01:02:07,760
laterally to a different team and seeing if 
you can work there. I'd find the leaders who  

734
01:02:07,760 --> 01:02:11,880
know what they're doing and go work for 
that. That's usually the best move here.

735
01:02:11,880 --> 01:02:16,040
The point you made about how a lot of companies 
don't have any product owners and have scaled  

736
01:02:16,040 --> 01:02:21,480
very wide, just to reinforce that in the 
data dive that we did on job market trends,  

737
01:02:21,480 --> 01:02:28,920
no tech company has a product owner basically, 
no top tech company. I know there's an important  

738
01:02:28,920 --> 01:02:32,920
distinction here. These are tech, software first, 
product first businesses where their business  

739
01:02:32,920 --> 01:02:36,880
is the software they're building, and a lot of 
the companies we're talking about here are not  

740
01:02:36,880 --> 01:02:42,000
that. They're banks and telecoms, pharmaceutical 
companies. I get that it's a very different world,  

741
01:02:42,000 --> 01:02:46,600
but I think it's important to highlight, "You 
can become very big." Google has no product  

742
01:02:46,600 --> 01:02:52,000
owners as far as I know, Amazon, Microsoft, 
Netflix, no company you've heard of that's  

743
01:02:52,000 --> 01:02:56,720
a tech company has a product owner. They're all 
product managers, they're all product managers.

744
01:02:56,720 --> 01:03:02,440
Yeah. I don't want people to think that there 
aren't people who build great software in  

745
01:03:02,440 --> 01:03:06,360
these large corporations too because there are. 
There's pockets of people who are doing it super,  

746
01:03:06,360 --> 01:03:13,480
super well. If you are one of those people who's 
been pushing the boundaries, doing great work,  

747
01:03:13,480 --> 01:03:16,920
and your title is a product owner, what I always 
tell people on your resume, if you're looking for  

748
01:03:16,920 --> 01:03:23,080
your next job so that you're not pushed out, let's 
say, of these large corporations like a Google or  

749
01:03:23,080 --> 01:03:28,000
somewhere like that, and that's where you want 
to work in a tech firm, make sure you describe  

750
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:33,760
how you did your job from a value perspective. Do 
not talk about your agile cadences. Get Scrum out  

751
01:03:33,760 --> 01:03:38,120
of there. Talk about what value you brought 
to the users and what metrics you moved,  

752
01:03:38,120 --> 01:03:43,160
and that's how your resume should be laid out.
I do read tons of resumes to hire people,  

753
01:03:43,160 --> 01:03:49,880
and also chief product officer, same thing. If I 
see immediately implemented Scrum processes across  

754
01:03:49,880 --> 01:03:53,960
the organization, I'm like, "No, that's not what 
I need. That's not what I was looking for." I was  

755
01:03:53,960 --> 01:03:58,120
looking for what are you going to do to push the 
strategy in that part of the organization? What  

756
01:03:58,120 --> 01:04:01,240
are you going to do to actually build better 
products for customers? Then when you get into  

757
01:04:01,240 --> 01:04:05,680
the interview, you can talk about what things 
you did to do that, but you want to make sure  

758
01:04:05,680 --> 01:04:10,720
that you're focused on really understanding the 
customer and translating that into great products,  

759
01:04:10,720 --> 01:04:15,040
and the outcomes that we were looking for when you 
do it on your resume, I think that's important.

760
01:04:15,040 --> 01:04:19,160
Okay. I want to spend more time here because 
this is so important. This is highlighting  

761
01:04:19,160 --> 01:04:23,840
here's the difference between a product owner 
and a product manager. If you want to move  

762
01:04:23,840 --> 01:04:28,400
into product management and become a great PM, if 
you're a product owner today, even if you're not a  

763
01:04:28,400 --> 01:04:32,360
product owner and just want to get into product 
management, can you again just highlight here's  

764
01:04:32,360 --> 01:04:38,480
the big difference and here's the skills that 
people value most in a PM versus a product owner.

765
01:04:38,480 --> 01:04:44,920
Yeah. When I see product owners write out 
their resumes or describe their job functions,  

766
01:04:44,920 --> 01:04:49,760
they always approach it from a process standpoint. 
I prioritize the backlog, I worked with the  

767
01:04:49,760 --> 01:04:54,600
developers to break down the work, I checked the 
developer's work and did the acceptance criteria,  

768
01:04:54,600 --> 01:04:59,360
I wrote the user stories, all those functions is 
what I see over and over and over again in product  

769
01:04:59,360 --> 01:05:07,440
owner resume. What you want to do instead is say, 
"I led the," we can even do the login API,"I led  

770
01:05:07,440 --> 01:05:12,640
the work around the login API. The problem 
that I was solving around it was trying to  

771
01:05:12,640 --> 01:05:18,080
enhance security for our login protocols to meet 
regulatory requirements. I interviewed a bunch  

772
01:05:18,080 --> 01:05:21,560
of users, I got up to speed on the regulatory 
requirements, I worked really closely with our  

773
01:05:21,560 --> 01:05:26,680
legal teams and our compliance teams to translate 
that into something that was going to secure our  

774
01:05:26,680 --> 01:05:32,040
bank, and when we launched, we were able to meet 
our compliance, save our bank a couple million  

775
01:05:32,040 --> 01:05:36,800
dollars, and we smoothly transitioned into these 
new security requirements without disrupting any  

776
01:05:36,800 --> 01:05:42,800
service for customers for four million customers."
Way different story than I prioritized backlog and  

777
01:05:42,800 --> 01:05:47,640
I shipped it off to developers. Take it a step 
further. If you're working on customer-facing  

778
01:05:47,640 --> 01:05:52,160
things, who are your customers? Did you 
go out and talk to them? By interfacing  

779
01:05:52,160 --> 01:05:57,000
with customers and understanding them, I was 
able to solve XY, and Z problem with them,  

780
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:03,480
which resulted in a measurable amount of XY 
and Z metric going up for the business. I ran  

781
01:06:03,480 --> 01:06:08,520
this function, I ran this feature, I launched this 
feature, I watched it through, I iterated on it,  

782
01:06:08,520 --> 01:06:14,880
I did the stuff that was needed to make this 
successful. That's what I want to see on a resume. 

783
01:06:14,880 --> 01:06:20,120
Even if you have a product owner title, I'll still 
read the details and everybody else will too,  

784
01:06:20,120 --> 01:06:24,280
but I will say there's sometimes a poor 
connotation when you have that title  

785
01:06:24,280 --> 01:06:29,520
unfortunately because of the baggage that's 
associated with agile. Even just on resumes,  

786
01:06:29,520 --> 01:06:35,640
I would say do product owner/product manager 
in there just to let people know that I know  

787
01:06:35,640 --> 01:06:40,000
how to do this and I've been doing this 
well. If you do that in your bullet points,  

788
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:45,160
that shows up as well. There's also this whole 
concept that we didn't even get into about  

789
01:06:45,160 --> 01:06:51,240
certifications. People keep asking me if I want 
to transition into product management, should I  

790
01:06:51,240 --> 01:06:55,640
get a certification, an agile certification?" I 
feel like these were bigger a couple years ago,  

791
01:06:55,640 --> 01:07:00,400
but they're still big. If you ever see somebody 
with a CSPO on the end of their profile,  

792
01:07:00,400 --> 01:07:05,720
which you probably have seen on LinkedIn, 
it's a certified Scrum product owner. 

793
01:07:05,720 --> 01:07:13,640
Now, one thing to remember, and this is about all 
agile stuff, is we call it the agile industrial  

794
01:07:13,640 --> 01:07:21,200
complex, agile coaches and agile trainers, 
the whole Scrum team, scrum.org, Scrum Inc,  

795
01:07:21,200 --> 01:07:25,520
SAFe, everybody, the way they make their money is 
through consulting to teach you these processes  

796
01:07:26,120 --> 01:07:31,600
and by having people be trained to get these 
certifications. They come in and they say,  

797
01:07:31,600 --> 01:07:37,240
"All your people need to be certified Scrum 
product owners. Give me 2,500 bucks per person,"  

798
01:07:37,240 --> 01:07:40,960
and then they get a certificate at the end of 
a two-day class that says they're a certified  

799
01:07:40,960 --> 01:07:46,080
Scrum product owner. It doesn't necessarily mean 
they could do the job, it doesn't necessarily mean  

800
01:07:46,080 --> 01:07:50,560
they could do product management, but let's think 
about when we're talking about too should we adopt  

801
01:07:50,560 --> 01:07:55,440
SAFe in general, should we adopt these things, 
think about how these organizations make money. 

802
01:07:56,760 --> 01:08:01,520
They're selling certifications. Of course they 
want more and more people to adopt it. That's the  

803
01:08:01,520 --> 01:08:07,920
idea here. They're selling you this dream that you 
just certify all your people and then you could  

804
01:08:07,920 --> 01:08:13,120
be working on it. They take all these people, 
they put them in two-day classes or whatever,  

805
01:08:13,120 --> 01:08:17,440
and they turn them out and then they say, "Go, 
you're a completely new role." It doesn't work  

806
01:08:17,440 --> 01:08:20,960
that way. That's not in the best interest of your 
company, that's not really what we're looking for  

807
01:08:20,960 --> 01:08:26,360
here, and that's why all of this stuff needs to go 
deeper. If you've done a CSPO class and you have  

808
01:08:26,360 --> 01:08:32,840
that certification, it may help you get hired at 
another large enterprise that is adopting Scrum  

809
01:08:32,840 --> 01:08:38,120
and SAFe. That will probably help you there.
If you want to transition into tech and go into  

810
01:08:38,120 --> 01:08:41,560
the companies that we talk about, they're 
probably going to look at that and say,  

811
01:08:41,560 --> 01:08:46,120
"This person doesn't know what they're 
doing. This is not here." If you do know  

812
01:08:46,120 --> 01:08:50,520
what you're doing and you did that for a reason, 
because some people need that to get promoted,  

813
01:08:50,520 --> 01:08:55,440
some companies actually require it, which is 
crazy, but to get promoted or be that thing,  

814
01:08:56,320 --> 01:08:59,640
I have tremendous sympathy for that, but you're 
going to have to do a lot of work explaining in  

815
01:08:59,640 --> 01:09:04,280
your resumes and stuff as you transition that 
you know more than that. You're not just a CSPO  

816
01:09:04,800 --> 01:09:09,000
with a two-day class, you have done the work. 
That's where all of this building up on your  

817
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:13,520
resume becomes really, really important. 
It's not just about getting certified. 

818
01:09:14,560 --> 01:09:18,840
I had people ask me, they're like, "Can you 
just certify product managers?" I'm like,  

819
01:09:18,840 --> 01:09:22,560
"No. If people take my course, I give them a 
certificate of completion and as a completion."  

820
01:09:22,560 --> 01:09:27,280
You finished a course just like any other course, 
but I will not certify product managers because I  

821
01:09:27,280 --> 01:09:37,360
do not think you can ever say somebody is prepared 
and able to do their job from a short class. Now,  

822
01:09:38,840 --> 01:09:45,080
there are some agile agencies that do a lot more 
training where you have different levels, and what  

823
01:09:45,080 --> 01:09:48,720
they would do is they would train people, but then 
they would make them go do work and they had a  

824
01:09:48,720 --> 01:09:52,440
coach that they worked with, and they go back and 
forth and they could demonstrate that they could  

825
01:09:52,440 --> 01:09:58,840
do the work over time to get to the next level.
It's almost like the PMP, the project management  

826
01:09:58,840 --> 01:10:03,600
certification where you have to have time 
actually doing the job. That's different,  

827
01:10:03,600 --> 01:10:08,760
that's a different type of skill, it's a different 
type of certification, but if you see any CSPOs,  

828
01:10:08,760 --> 01:10:13,960
it's typically a two-day workshop that they 
went to and then got certified. That's the  

829
01:10:13,960 --> 01:10:18,840
difference with this. I would say be careful if 
you are a product owner wanting to be a product  

830
01:10:18,840 --> 01:10:25,880
manager of just certifications. All the large tech 
organizations I know too, they're not looking for  

831
01:10:25,880 --> 01:10:29,760
certifications in product management or product 
ownership to hire people, they're looking for  

832
01:10:29,760 --> 01:10:34,280
experience, but the organizations that might 
not know what they're doing, they are looking  

833
01:10:34,280 --> 01:10:39,960
for CSPOs, they are looking for that.
If it's required by your organization,  

834
01:10:39,960 --> 01:10:47,240
you might have to ask, "Are we all well set up 
here to do our best job? Is this the place where  

835
01:10:47,240 --> 01:10:51,080
I'm going to learn how to be a better product 
manager?" I also feel bad though for people  

836
01:10:51,080 --> 01:10:53,920
because it's hard to be a product manager, 
it's hard to get your foot in the door.  

837
01:10:56,040 --> 01:11:02,680
I'm so torn on it because there are organizations 
that hire people with a CSPO and they require it,  

838
01:11:02,680 --> 01:11:09,440
so of course if it gets your foot in the door and 
it helps you do it, but if it's not going to help  

839
01:11:09,440 --> 01:11:14,840
you and it's not going to put you on the career 
path you want, I don't think it's worth money.

840
01:11:14,840 --> 01:11:19,280
I think one interesting thread throughout 
this whole conversation is rarely is a  

841
01:11:19,280 --> 01:11:24,000
plug-in play-ish easy solution going 
to be the answer to your problem,  

842
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:27,480
whether it's plugging in SAFe and it's 
going to help us build great software,  

843
01:11:27,480 --> 01:11:31,480
taking a class helping you become a great 
product manager, be skeptical of that.

844
01:11:32,000 --> 01:11:34,600
Yeah. There's no quick way to doing any of this,  

845
01:11:34,600 --> 01:11:39,160
there's no fast track. You don't get 
to skip over all the hard things.

846
01:11:39,160 --> 01:11:40,600
Yeah. Bummer.

847
01:11:40,600 --> 01:11:42,900
Yeah. I wish.

848
01:11:42,900 --> 01:11:47,400
Yeah. One question I wanted to clarify. When you 
come into an org and they have product owners,  

849
01:11:47,400 --> 01:11:50,360
do you encourage them to get rid of 
product owner as a title and role  

850
01:11:50,360 --> 01:11:53,480
and make them product managers 
or do you keep product owners?

851
01:11:53,480 --> 01:11:59,520
I say that we should have a hierarchy. You 
would have all product managers on a team,  

852
01:12:01,040 --> 01:12:05,120
they would be an IC, individual contributor, so 
they're either an associate product manager and  

853
01:12:05,120 --> 01:12:10,400
that's if they don't have all the discovery 
experience or maybe they know basic Scrum,  

854
01:12:10,400 --> 01:12:13,160
totally fine, you can be an associate product 
manager, but if they don't know how to talk  

855
01:12:13,160 --> 01:12:18,760
to customers, digest what the customers are 
saying and turn that into a feature direction  

856
01:12:18,760 --> 01:12:23,360
and a backlog and this is how we're going to 
work, all that stuff needs to be in there.  

857
01:12:23,360 --> 01:12:28,160
If they don't know how they should be measuring 
things, you're not quite a product manager yet. 

858
01:12:28,160 --> 01:12:31,840
Associate product manager, and then product 
manager, and then a senior PM. A senior PM  

859
01:12:31,840 --> 01:12:35,880
can work on a Scrum team as well or a 
development team. I do encourage them,  

860
01:12:35,880 --> 01:12:42,040
I say, "Get rid of these two different titles 
because it's confusing everybody." I help a  

861
01:12:42,040 --> 01:12:46,040
lot of people with career paths too. I've 
seen companies with 47 different titles  

862
01:12:46,040 --> 01:12:51,440
for product managers because somebody in this 
organization is called a product associate and  

863
01:12:51,440 --> 01:12:55,520
somebody over here is a product manager and 
that person is a platform product manager,  

864
01:12:55,520 --> 01:13:00,840
and that person is a platform product owner, 
and this person is an API product owner. You  

865
01:13:00,840 --> 01:13:07,200
can have product manager, senior product 
manager, all that stuff, but I would not  

866
01:13:07,200 --> 01:13:11,560
confuse people with the two different titles 
of product owner versus product manager.

867
01:13:11,560 --> 01:13:17,280
But importantly, there's a bar for who 
is called a product manager because  

868
01:13:17,280 --> 01:13:20,040
if you take a product owner as you've 
said, and say you're a product manager,  

869
01:13:20,040 --> 01:13:25,440
they're going to be a terrible product manager. 
Your advice is make them an associate PM, and then  

870
01:13:25,440 --> 01:13:28,520
once they reach a certain level, 
they've graduated to product manager.

871
01:13:28,520 --> 01:13:32,760
It depends. I don't say this as a hard and fast 
rule because there are product owners out there  

872
01:13:32,760 --> 01:13:35,880
who've been doing their job very well. Just 
because they have a title of a product owner  

873
01:13:35,880 --> 01:13:40,000
doesn't mean that somebody can't do the job of a 
product manager. There are plenty of people out  

874
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:44,480
there who were just named this because a company 
names them that and they know what they're doing,  

875
01:13:44,480 --> 01:13:50,480
so don't look at that hard and fast. When we 
do this, we typically will say everybody's  

876
01:13:50,480 --> 01:13:53,880
got product owner on their title, change 
it to product manager, but we will go back  

877
01:13:53,880 --> 01:13:58,000
and look at what is the actual skillset.
When I've come in to work with companies  

878
01:13:58,000 --> 01:14:02,720
on transformations, what we typically do, 
the way I get introduced usually is we come  

879
01:14:02,720 --> 01:14:06,480
in and they're looking for some kind of 
training for all of their product teams,  

880
01:14:06,480 --> 01:14:09,920
and then we bring in Product Institute and 
we do our online training, Then afterwards  

881
01:14:09,920 --> 01:14:14,440
I work with the organization, I say, "Now that 
everybody's been baselined and trained, we have  

882
01:14:14,440 --> 01:14:19,160
to figure out who is going to be a great product 
manager and who's not," so there's an awareness.  

883
01:14:19,160 --> 01:14:24,680
You know what's interesting? Once people figure 
out what the job's about, a lot of them opt out. 

884
01:14:24,680 --> 01:14:29,400
When I did the transformation at Athenahealth, 
we had 365 product managers and they all had  

885
01:14:29,960 --> 01:14:34,200
different titles too, product innovation, all over 
the place. We turned them into product managers,  

886
01:14:34,200 --> 01:14:38,040
we trained everybody, we gave everybody the 
opportunity to learn, which I think is great,  

887
01:14:38,040 --> 01:14:41,600
and then we gave them opportunity to 
practice their skills. What happened  

888
01:14:41,600 --> 01:14:44,760
is at the end of the training, a lot of 
people raised their hand and said, "Oh, no,  

889
01:14:44,760 --> 01:14:50,720
no, this is not what I wanted to do. I thought 
it was very different. I did not realize how  

890
01:14:50,720 --> 01:14:55,920
much people work it was. I have to go influence 
these people, I have to do all this stuff. This  

891
01:14:55,920 --> 01:15:02,120
is actually not really what I wanted to do."
We found other roles for them that were what  

892
01:15:02,120 --> 01:15:07,320
they wanted to do or they decided to leave. 
That was up to them, we didn't cut anybody,  

893
01:15:07,320 --> 01:15:12,160
but we moved some people into operations because 
they wanted to be a little more heads down to  

894
01:15:12,160 --> 01:15:17,040
find process. That was their thing. We moved 
people into data roles who were good with SQL  

895
01:15:17,040 --> 01:15:20,760
and were good with data analysis. We moved 
people into user research roles because they  

896
01:15:20,760 --> 01:15:24,560
wanted to talk to customers, but they didn't 
want the responsibility and the accountability  

897
01:15:24,560 --> 01:15:28,160
that came with the product management piece 
because they realized it was so intense. 

898
01:15:29,080 --> 01:15:33,040
I've seen this happen a lot in large 
organizations. You baseline everybody,  

899
01:15:34,080 --> 01:15:38,000
you show them what the role is and then you 
let them go practice it, and then at that point  

900
01:15:38,000 --> 01:15:43,200
some people will opt out and then you have to go 
back through your people and say, "Okay. How do  

901
01:15:43,200 --> 01:15:50,840
we level-set now? Who's doing really well? Who's 
not doing so well? Which teams need to have more  

902
01:15:50,840 --> 01:15:55,760
experienced people on it because they don't have 
anybody to learn from?" That's where we would say,  

903
01:15:55,760 --> 01:16:00,040
"Hey, let's hire some ICs over here or a director 
of product management who can help train these  

904
01:16:00,040 --> 01:16:05,160
people and help them keep growing." That's been 
super successful. I've seen people bring in  

905
01:16:05,160 --> 01:16:09,800
some more directors, scattered them around, 
and they've leveled up these product owners  

906
01:16:09,800 --> 01:16:13,600
who were not necessarily doing great product 
management and now they're doing fantastic. 

907
01:16:13,600 --> 01:16:19,680
I've watched fantastic leaders in these 
organizations that are not software native or  

908
01:16:19,680 --> 01:16:24,480
doing these transformations. Bringing the right 
person, you can make amazing product managers.  

909
01:16:25,520 --> 01:16:30,000
Give them a year or two and completely 
turn it around. It's totally possible.  

910
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:33,880
It's totally possible to take people and 
train them, and I firmly believe in that,  

911
01:16:33,880 --> 01:16:37,000
but you got to get them exposure 
to what good looks like. If you are  

912
01:16:37,000 --> 01:16:40,920
in an organization and you cannot 
see what good looks like anywhere,  

913
01:16:40,920 --> 01:16:45,440
that's a red flag. That's where leaders 
need to look at their organization and say,  

914
01:16:45,440 --> 01:16:50,960
"Do I have people with these skills interspersed 
around so that everybody can start to learn,  

915
01:16:50,960 --> 01:16:56,760
so that everybody can actually be on the uptake 
of this and make sure that we are well-balanced?"

916
01:16:56,760 --> 01:17:02,520
That was an awesome nuance and addition. I'm just 
looking back at all the things we've talked about.  

917
01:17:02,520 --> 01:17:09,760
We've covered so much ground, the history of 
agile and Scrum and SAFes and product owners,  

918
01:17:09,760 --> 01:17:14,720
we've gotten into all kinds of advice on 
how to do this better as a company leader,  

919
01:17:14,720 --> 01:17:18,760
as a product owner, as someone thinking about 
even moving through product management. Is there  

920
01:17:18,760 --> 01:17:25,000
anything else that we have not covered that you 
think might be helpful to touch on or wrap up on?

921
01:17:25,000 --> 01:17:29,440
I think I would tell people to remember 
that when you look at agile methodologies,  

922
01:17:29,440 --> 01:17:33,600
and if you look at it with small agile, what 
we are really saying there is we want to be  

923
01:17:33,600 --> 01:17:39,680
able to move quickly and deliver great value 
to customers. If you embrace those principles,  

924
01:17:39,680 --> 01:17:45,800
you're going to do well, but if you think 
of agile as just a defined super cut and  

925
01:17:45,800 --> 01:17:49,920
dry process where you have to follow 
every single little step here and there,  

926
01:17:49,920 --> 01:17:54,920
that's not going to serve you because you're 
not getting back into why are we doing this. 

927
01:17:54,920 --> 01:17:58,720
There are some great agile coaches out there. 
There are first principle approaches to doing  

928
01:17:58,720 --> 01:18:03,840
great product work and doing great development 
work. They're there because they are not just  

929
01:18:03,840 --> 01:18:08,840
selling Scrum, they are there to make people 
better. Those agile coaches I think can make  

930
01:18:08,840 --> 01:18:12,960
great fantastic teams, and I've worked with a 
lot of them, and I think they are really there  

931
01:18:12,960 --> 01:18:18,080
to just make it a better environment for the 
people who are working and to help the company  

932
01:18:18,080 --> 01:18:24,920
produce better products. That's their whole goal.
Then there are people too who are wedded to this  

933
01:18:24,920 --> 01:18:28,600
is SAFe and you will do it by the book. This is 
Scrum, you will do it by the book. I'd be very  

934
01:18:28,600 --> 01:18:36,400
skeptical of that because what's the end goal? 
What's their end goal? Like I said, a lot of  

935
01:18:36,400 --> 01:18:42,520
people out there get paid by certifying people 
and by consulting on these processes. McKinsey  

936
01:18:42,520 --> 01:18:47,960
made a huge division to do this, and a lot of 
SAFe was actually introduced to organizations  

937
01:18:47,960 --> 01:18:52,280
from McKinsey and from large organizations, 
consulting organizations like that. They came  

938
01:18:52,280 --> 01:18:55,760
in and they said, "Yeah, this is what you do. 
I'll teach you how to do SAFe, I'll teach you  

939
01:18:55,760 --> 01:19:02,280
how to do Scrum." They have been building those 
consulting agencies off of agile transformations. 

940
01:19:03,280 --> 01:19:08,360
We always laugh when I talk to other people who've 
been doing transformations and coaches. I go,  

941
01:19:08,360 --> 01:19:11,760
"Why is McKinsey always coming in here 
and doing this?" I've followed them into  

942
01:19:11,760 --> 01:19:16,320
so many organizations and I've been like, "Oh, 
wow, they screwed this up. Let me go fix it."  

943
01:19:17,040 --> 01:19:22,880
There's always a saying that nobody gets 
fired for hiring McKinsey. McKinsey's big,  

944
01:19:22,880 --> 01:19:28,880
people trust their name. A lot of the people at 
McKinsey haven't done this before, they've never  

945
01:19:28,880 --> 01:19:34,360
been inside the organization trying to transform 
it and stay there for a long time. That's why I'd  

946
01:19:34,360 --> 01:19:40,600
be really skeptical of who's selling that.
If you approach agile from a perspective of  

947
01:19:40,600 --> 01:19:44,960
I want to be agile because I want to release 
things quickly and get feedback from customers  

948
01:19:44,960 --> 01:19:48,720
and make sure that that's great, look at 
all of your processes like that and say,  

949
01:19:48,720 --> 01:19:55,960
"Is that serving the best interest of our company 
and our culture and our customers? Is this making  

950
01:19:55,960 --> 01:20:02,280
our customers proud of us? Is this helping our 
customers receive good value?" If your processes  

951
01:20:02,280 --> 01:20:09,480
aren't, fix them, change them, inspect and adapt, 
ease a lowercase agile principle. We should be  

952
01:20:09,480 --> 01:20:15,360
looking at every process we do and saying, "Is 
it working?", and not be afraid to change it.

953
01:20:15,360 --> 01:20:21,160
I think it's important to highlight this can 
work. There are ways to reorganize the way you  

954
01:20:21,160 --> 01:20:26,480
build product at a very large company where you 
can actually deliver great product consistently.  

955
01:20:26,480 --> 01:20:30,960
You've seen that happen a lot. Anything 
you want to add there to give people hope?

956
01:20:30,960 --> 01:20:35,800
Yeah. The biggest pushback I hear from large 
organizations, especially ones that are not  

957
01:20:35,800 --> 01:20:40,960
software native as banks or insurance companies, 
whatever it is, is that we're not like Google,  

958
01:20:40,960 --> 01:20:46,280
we're not like SaaS companies. It's true, you're 
not a SaaS company. The way that you do it is  

959
01:20:46,280 --> 01:20:51,800
going to be slightly different than the way that 
Amazon runs or the way that Google runs. I don't  

960
01:20:51,800 --> 01:20:56,880
see many companies actually run the same, and just 
because it works at Google doesn't mean it's going  

961
01:20:56,880 --> 01:21:04,040
to work at an insurance company that's a hundred 
years old. That's okay, but you could still learn  

962
01:21:04,040 --> 01:21:10,720
from people who've been producing software at 
scale for many, many years. You can still learn  

963
01:21:10,720 --> 01:21:14,560
what makes them successful, and then you could 
take some of those principles and apply them  

964
01:21:14,560 --> 01:21:19,720
to your organization and then figure out where 
we need to adapt. That's what I would look at. 

965
01:21:21,320 --> 01:21:27,680
I see software strategies and digital strategies 
becoming so intertwined into the strategies of  

966
01:21:27,680 --> 01:21:32,080
companies in general, whether you're an 
insurance company or a bank or anything.  

967
01:21:32,720 --> 01:21:38,640
They're becoming so heavily entwined in the 
C-suite strategies. The first thing I would say,  

968
01:21:38,640 --> 01:21:42,760
and where I see a lot of companies struggle with 
this is you have to make sure that it is thought  

969
01:21:42,760 --> 01:21:49,240
of at the C-suite. What some organizations do is 
go, "Oh, no, that's IT work. Let me push all the  

970
01:21:49,240 --> 01:21:54,200
software strategy down." If you're doing that, 
you're missing out on innovation, and this is  

971
01:21:54,200 --> 01:21:59,200
where the product role comes in and where I think 
more organizations need chief product officers  

972
01:21:59,200 --> 01:22:05,240
because they're the person in the C-suite saying, 
"How can software enable us to be 10 times better  

973
01:22:05,240 --> 01:22:09,680
and crush our competition, whether we're a bank 
or insurance company or a pharmaceutical company?  

974
01:22:10,240 --> 01:22:14,200
What can we do with our software that's 
going to put us ahead of the competition,  

975
01:22:14,200 --> 01:22:19,040
that's going to put us ahead of the market?"
If you're not having those conversations when  

976
01:22:19,040 --> 01:22:22,720
you're thinking of your long-term 
company strategy, you're behind,  

977
01:22:22,720 --> 01:22:28,320
you're behind because that is what every small 
high-growth startup is doing that's coming out  

978
01:22:28,320 --> 01:22:32,760
to try to disrupt these big companies. The 
big companies are successful, they have a lot  

979
01:22:32,760 --> 01:22:37,080
of money so they don't have as much urgency as 
sometimes these smaller companies do to change  

980
01:22:37,080 --> 01:22:41,720
or somebody who's failing to change. That's why 
things are going so slow, but at the same time,  

981
01:22:41,720 --> 01:22:46,760
if we don't pay attention to that and we're not 
considering it, that's where the danger comes in.

